hat the Bible teaches about human nature, and that central Hellenic figures from outside the philosophical mainstream – notably Homer and Sophocles – are ‘biblical’ in orientation. Each of Glouberman’s theses lends new depth to contemporary research on the Bible as a source of material that illuminates the human condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophical anthropologyzGreecexHistory. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aTheological anthropologyxBiblical teaching. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266218640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662186.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK